{
  "local_port": 34622,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I remove the HTC One X System folder, which still appears on my Windows 7 list of devices?",
  "response": "If the \"HTC One X System folder\" is still appearing in your list of devices on Windows 7, it might be a residual entry from a previous connection or an improperly uninstalled driver. Below are several methods you can use to remove this lingering device from your system:\n\n---\n\n### **Method 1: Using Device Manager**\n\n1. **Disconnect Your Device:**\n   - Ensure that your HTC One X is disconnected from your computer.\n\n2. **Open Device Manager:**\n   - Click the **Start** button.\n   - Right-click on **Computer** and select **Manage**.\n   - In the **Computer Management** window, select **Device Manager** from the left pane.\n\n3. **Show Hidden Devices:**\n   - In Device Manager, click on the **View** menu.\n   - Select **Show hidden devices** to display devices that are not currently connected.\n\n4. **Locate the HTC One X Entry:**\n   - Expand categories such as **Portable Devices**, **Universal Serial Bus controllers**, or **Disk drives**.\n   - Look for entries named **HTC One X System folder** or similar.\n\n5. **Uninstall the Device:**\n   - Right-click on the HTC One X entry.\n   - Select **Uninstall**.\n   - Confirm any prompts to remove the driver.\n\n6. **Restart Your Computer:**\n   - After uninstalling, restart your computer to apply the changes.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 2: Using Devices and Printers**\n\n1. **Open Devices and Printers:**\n   - Click the **Start** button.\n   - Go to **Control Panel** > **Devices and Printers**.\n\n2. **Find the HTC One X System Folder:**\n   - Browse through the list of devices to locate the **HTC One X System folder**.\n\n3. **Remove the Device:**\n   - Right-click on the device.\n   - Select **Remove device**.\n   - Confirm the removal when prompted.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 3: Using the Registry Editor (Advanced Users)**\n\n**\u26a0\ufe0f Warning:** Editing the registry can be risky. It's highly recommended to back up the registry before making any changes.\n\n1. **Open Registry Editor:**\n   - Press **Win + R**, type `regedit`, and press **Enter**.\n\n2. **Navigate to USB Entries:**\n   - Go to `HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Enum\\USB\\`.\n   - You might also check `HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Enum\\USBSTOR\\`.\n\n3. **Find the HTC One X Entry:**\n   - Browse through the folders to find entries related to **HTC One X** or **System folder**.\n\n4. **Delete the Entry:**\n   - Right-click on the relevant entry and select **Delete**.\n   - Confirm any prompts to remove the entry.\n\n5. **Restart Your Computer:**\n   - Close the Registry Editor and restart your computer to apply changes.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 4: Using Third-Party Software (USBDeview)**\n\n1. **Download USBDeview:**\n   - Visit the [NirSoft USBDeview](https://www.nirsoft.net/utils/usb_devices_view.html) website.\n   - Download the utility and extract the files.\n\n2. **Run USBDeview:**\n   - Execute the `USBDeview.exe` file as an administrator.\n\n3. **Locate the HTC One X Entry:**\n   - In the list of USB devices, find the **HTC One X System folder**.\n\n4. **Delete the Device:**\n   - Right-click on the entry.\n   - Select **Delete Selected Devices**.\n   - Confirm the deletion when prompted.\n\n5. **Restart Your Computer:**\n   - After deletion, restart your computer.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 5: Update or Reinstall Drivers**\n\n1. **Download Latest Drivers:**\n   - Visit the [HTC Support](https://www.htc.com/support/) website.\n   - Download the latest drivers for the HTC One X.\n\n2. **Install the Drivers:**\n   - Run the driver installer and follow the on-screen instructions.\n\n3. **Reconnect Your Device:**\n   - After installation, reconnect your HTC One X.\n   - This might refresh the device listing and remove any incorrect entries.\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n\n- **Check for Physical Connections:** Ensure that no HTC One X device is connected to your computer during the removal process to prevent automatic reinstallation.\n  \n- **Run a Clean Boot:** If the device reappears after following the above steps, try performing a clean boot to determine if startup programs are causing the issue.\n\n- **Scan for Malware:** Sometimes, unwanted system entries can be caused by malware. Run a comprehensive antivirus scan to rule out this possibility.\n\n- **System File Checker:** Run `sfc /scannow` in Command Prompt to check and repair corrupted system files that might be causing device listing issues.\n\n---\n\nBy following these methods, you should be able to successfully remove the \"HTC One X System folder\" from your Windows 7 list of devices. If the problem persists after trying all the above steps, consider seeking professional technical support or reaching out to HTC's customer service for further assistance.",
